<TEXT>
ras albisha iraq ap the iraqis manning their armys 
southernmost observation post on the iraniraq ceasefire line lay 
in the sun idly watching the iranians in their outpost a few 
hundred yards across the mouth of the shattalarab waterway 
the iranians do the same peering through binoculars across the 
estuary that flows into the persian gulf 
the soldiers on both sides are waiting for a peace treaty between 
their governments that will allow them to go home 
the only sounds to intrude on the overpowering quiet are the 
cries of sea gulls that wheel above and the waves from the gulf 
breaking on the seaweedstrewn beach 
the soldiers biggest problem is the boredom and the hordes of 
bugs that buzz over the marshy shoreline 
despite reports of violations of the 7monthold ceasefire 
further north life in what was one of the bloodiest battlegrounds 
of the 8year iraniraq war has assumed a sleepy tranquility 
weve plenty of time now for fishing playing cards and 
reading says the iraqi officer who commands the small squad 
manning the sandbagged post 
dont do that a young iraqi lieutenant quips as a reporter 
tries to photograph the remains of an iranianbuilt bridge and a 
sunken vessel the iranians will take that as a violation of the 
ceasefire 
eleven months ago this area was under constant iraqi air and 
artillery attack the main target the concrete bridge the iranians 
built to link the bridgehead on iraqs faw peninsula that they 
captured in february 1986 
for two years the iraqis tried and failed to dislodge iranians 
dug in around the marshlands ringing the battered oil terminal town 
of faw 
then last april they launched a surprise attack after weeks of 
diversions and stealthy infiltration and recaptured faw in a 36hour 
battle 
it was the first of a chain of victories that pushed the iranians 
out of all iraqi territory they had overrun and forced tehran to 
unconditionally accept a un ceasefire resolution 
a large sign erected at the entrance to faw says 52948 iraqis 
and more than 120000 iranians were killed in the battles for the 
sandy peninsula 
the iraqi toll was the first indication that reporters for 
western news organizations have had of the scale of baghdads 
losses unofficial estimates have put the iraqi death toll for the 
whole war at around 150000 
the claim of 120000 iranians killed merely in the fighting for 
faw is impossible to verify the iranians have only admitted to some 
130000 dead for the whole war although western analysts estimate 
that is only a fraction of the true total 
iranian losses generally were considered to be at least three 
times the iraqi casualties mainly because of the carnage in the 
iranians human wave attacks against the wellentrenched iraqis 
iraqi officers said more than 65 million shells were fired by 
the two armies during the iranian occupation of faw 
the ruined town one of the few iraqi towns overrun by the 
iranians stands as a symbol of our sacrifices and heroism said 
anwar saeed alhadithi governor of nearby basra 
he told the associated press that plans have been completed to 
build a new urban center in faw to replace the old town 
iraqi authorities last year launched a nationwide donation 
campaign to collect money to rebuild faw which had a prewar 
population of 56000 
similar drives were launched in neighboring kuwait and other 
persian gulf countries 
reliable iraqi sources say millions of dollars have been 
collected for the reconstruction which is expected to start next 
month on the anniversary of the liberation of faw 
the government has not spelled out its plans for the faw port 
which before the war was a key oil export outlet to japan and europe 
rebuilding the port cannot start until iran and iraq reach 
agreement in their deadlocked peace talks on clearing the 
120milelong shattalarab of sunken ships war debris and silt 
</TEXT>
