<TEXT>
residents of the northern united states were treated to a rare 
display of the northern lights this morning and a scientist 
said there is a good chance of more celestial light shows all week 
clouds blocked the show for many but people in several states 
including colorado new york and delaware saw the night sky glow 
various colors from a whitish green to a brilliant red late sunday 
and early today the national weather service reported 
ron king of radio station ksl in salt lake city described the 
lights which appeared over the great salt lake about 4 am mst 
today as a shimmering cloud in the sky of vivid reds and 
purples that lasted for about a half hour 
the northern lights or aurora borealis are usually visible only 
near the arctic circle 
the phenomenon is believed to result from the interaction of tiny 
charged particles from the sun with gases in the earths upper 
atmosphere 
a solar flare reported thursday described by experts as the 
largest in five years apparently triggered the unusually widespread 
northern lights 
joe allen solarterrestrial expert at the national oceanic and 
atmospheric administration in boulder colo said observatories 
from san juan puerto rico to honolulu detected the shower of tiny 
charged particles sunday night 
all of them have a beautiful record of the event it started 
about 630 pm mst sunday and kept increasing over a period of at 
least nine hours he said today 
allen said there was a good chance all week of further displays 
of northern lights across the northern third of the united states 
in delaware on sunday state police received reports from 
residents about strangely lit clouds police concluded it was the 
aurora borealis after checking for reports of military rocket tests 
or power plant problems in the region 
researchers reported that thursdays huge eruption of gas from 
the surface of the sun was followed by another large explosion 
friday morning and three more on saturday all in the same area of 
the sun 
its a very disturbed area probably two to three earths in 
diameter said tom folkers a technical specialist and telescope 
operator at kitt peak national observatory near tucson ariz 
besides causing the aurora borealis solar flares can disrupt 
radio communications 
