momentarily monday but resumed later monday night 
on nov 29 1988 the soviets stopped jamming radio liberty and 
several other foreign radio stations including west germanys 
deutsche welle and the voice of israel 
that step was heralded as another move in president mikhail s 
gorbachevs campaign for glasnost or greater openness 
mityunov said radio liberty was jammed monday night as it 
broadcast a report about a demonstration sunday in moscow in honor 
of the 1917 february revolution which toppled russias czardom the 
bolsheviks seized power later that year sweeping away the 
provisional government established in february 
mityunov said an editorial he wrote also was jammed he said his 
editorial accused moscow party boss lev n zaikov a member of the 
politburo of trying to prevent the nomination of his predecessor 
maverick communist boris n yeltsin as a candidate in the march 26 
elections to a new national assembly 
mityunov held the recever of his telephone up to his radio so the 
whine of the jamming was audible 
they used to call this khrushchev music or brezhnev 
music he said referring to former leaders nikita s khrushchev 
and leonid i brezhnev now well have to call it gorbachev 
music 
</TEXT>
