<TEXT>
jesse jackson was not among allies anything 
but so when they lectured him on political science he lectured 
right back 
in the resulting standoff the edge belonged to jackson the 
twice and future candidate for the white house 
the issue is not just who leads us but who needs us the 
black leader from chicago told establishment democrats who know 
well that they badly need him to stand a chance regaining the 
presidency in 1992 
it was all quite polite but the lines were clear at the 
democratic leadership council conference this past weekend centrist 
and conservative democrats organized the council four years ago 
after the landslide defeat of walter f mondales ticket in an 
effort to turn the party toward what they consider the voter 
mainstream 
jackson does not accept their map of the mainstream 
he suggested there was more to be learned about the next 
presidential election on the eastern airlines picket lines than in a 
seminar at a philadelphia hotel 
jackson told the council that white airline pilots who make 
140000 a year are on his side now because he went to their sides 
i am one of the few people around this table who has a net gain in 
white supporters he told the conference of democratic workers and 
officeholders i understand how to get white votes 
jackson and the democratic leadership council stand on opposite 
sides in the argument over a route back from five defeats in the 
past six presidential elections 
after a campaign in which republicans made the word liberal 
into a political curse most of the democrats at the philadelphia 
conference want a change in the message and a move toward the 
middle jackson insists that the party can win by mobilizing its own 
constituency and sticking to its own message 
the council called in a political science professor for advice 
and he said the problem is with swing voters not with turnout 
william a galston of the university of maryland said if everyone 
eligible had voted in 1988 president bush would have been elected 
by an even wider margin 
democratic support is hemorrhaging in the heart of the 
electorate said sen sam nunn of georgia sen charles s robb of 
virginia said democrats have to win back the middle class and cant 
afford the us against them perception he said has taken hold 
galston said that to have a chance the 1992 nominee must be 
fully credible as commander in chief must respond to the majority 
of voters who favor the death penalty and a generally tougher stance 
on crime and must reassure the middle class 
jackson listened politely but if there had been an exam on the 
galston lecture he would have flunked 
he offered his summation outside the conference room if we are 
all things to all people we become rather illdefined indecisive 
kind of like warm spit 
at least jackson was there listening and talking to democrats 
who know that his power will remain their problem he ran first in 
13 states and second in 33 in contests for democratic delegates in 
1988 and he shows no signs of slowing 
nunn said that despite their differences i also acknowledge 
him to be one of the people in the country who has the largest 
following and the people who support him are an extremely 
important element in the democratic party 
important enough that none of the establishment democrats picked 
a real fight over jacksons stance back home in chicago where he is 
supporting a thirdparty black candidate against richard m daley 
the democratic nominee for mayor 
robb did mention it saying jacksons refusal to support the 
primary winner could be a problem for him in 1992 jackson insists 
that the presidential primary elections and party caucuses should 
choose democratic presidential nominees without intervention by 
party leaders 
let the primary process determine the winner in 1992 jackson 
said in philadelphia 
but in discussing the chicago race jackson said he had supported 
daley twice in other elections and hes not endorsed me once 
you should support people who support you jackson said 
noting that some of those who criticize him now have refused to 
support black nominees in the past what is sacred are 
relationships honorable reciprocal relationships what is sacred 
is not the primary 
thats a line that may be replayed when presidential primaries 
are again the issue 
