<DOCNO> AP890313-0218 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
european finance ministers monday 
welcomed the new strategy offered by us treasury secretary 
nicholas brady to deal with the staggering foreign debts of 
developing nations 
the ministers of the 12nation european economic community 
however put off endorsing the plan until they had time to study it 
further 
it is a turning point said spanish finance minister carlos 
solchaga it is a change in the way we deal with the debt 
problem 
he said the developed nations will have to work with poorer 
nations on a casebycase basis to help solve the problem which 
will require a lot of imagination and cooperation 
the ministers meeting in a regular monthly session issued a 
statement saying they agreed with brady that the problem contains 
economic political and social elements and welcomed the openness of 
his approach 
they said they considered with interest the suggestions 
offered by brady and agreed that they merited thorough study 
bradys proposal marks a major shift in us debt policy by 
calling for an approach that emphasizes debt forgiveness to deal 
with the massive problem it endorses voluntary efforts on the part 
of commercial banks to forgive part of the 400 billion they are 
owed by the big debtor countries such as brazil mexico and 
venezuela 
it also calls on the international monetary fund and the world 
bank sister financing agencies to help provide guarantees for the 
remaining debt owed by poorer countries 
the united states had been following the baker plan which 
opposed writing off the third worlds debts to foreign creditors 
instead it urged commercial banks to boost their lending to poorer 
nations which agreed to make major changes in their economies for 
example by fighting inflation or bolstering a weak currency the 
plan was drawn up in 1985 by thentreasury secretary james baker 
who is currently secretary of state 
the finance officials said that voluntary debt or debt service 
reduction on a casebycase basis can play an important role in the 
success of sound economic plans 
they also urg if necessary ake changes in their regulatory and 
fiscal rules if necessary to enable commercial banks to reduce the 
debts 
solchaga noted that in many industrialized countries there are 
no regulations that would allow commercial banks to forgive the 
debts such measures should be adopted he said so the debt problem 
can be solved more easily 
the ministers statement also said developing countries must 
adopt deep economic reform policies if their economies are to 
expand at a lasting pace 
efforts to reverse capital flight must be strengthened it 
said both targets will include and be buttressed by increased 
openness of markets industrial countries should similarly ensure 
open and growing markets 
the ministers statement will be part of discussions at the 
spring meeting of the international monetary fund and world bank 
early next month in washington 
the foreign debt of developing countries registered a staggering 
13 trillion at the end of 1988 brazil is the third worlds 
largest debtor with 110 billion in loans followed by mexico with 
107 billion 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

