crude oil futures prices surged to a sevenweek 
high in moderate trading monday amid reports that fire forced the 
shutdown of a major norwegian oilproducing complex in the north sea 
on the new york mercantile exchange the april contract for west 
texas intermediate the benchmark grade of crude oil jumped 53 
cents to close at 1903 a barrel the last time the nearmonth 
contract closed above 19 a barrel was on jan 19 when it closed at 
1928 
other contract months also made strong gains monday with the may 
contract closing 54 cents higher at 1863 a barrel 
product prices continued to rise breaking through key technical 
levels analysts said 
the april contract for unleaded gasoline rose 138 cents to 
settle at 5316 cents a gallon while heating oil rose 116 cents to 
close at 5235 cents a gallon other contract months also posted 
strong gains 
analysts said a fire in a crude oil pump unit on a processing 
platform forced the closure of norways north sea ekofisk complex 
including seven crude oil fields 
the blaze was extinguished quickly but not before damaging 
surrounding cables and forcing the shutdown analysts said 
the seven fields produce an average of 250000 barrels a day of 
crude oil and about 1 billion cubic feet of gas 
phillips petroleum co of norway which operates the complex 
indicated the complex could be reopened within the next few days 
it was a strong day said jim fiedler vice president in 
charge of energy brokering for edampf man international futures 
inc fundamental news about ekofisk moved the market but there 
was an underlying strength before that 
traders said prices picked up steam as they broke through key 
technical levels that the market had resisted in recent weeks 
demand for oil products particularly heating oil have posted 
gains recently and continued strong in the wake of reports that 
european refiners were reducing refinery runs and product 
inventories 
