<TEXT>
a federal judge refused monday to dismiss 
claims that one of genentech incs major products an 
antiheartattack drug violated a rival firms patent 
us district judge marilyn hall patel ruled that abbott 
laboratories had produced enough evidence to go to trial on the 
question of whether its 1983 and 1985 patents were adequate to 
produce an artificial protein 
patel however also allowed genentech a south san francisco 
biotechnology company to make new legal attacks on abbotts patent 
including claims that it was not a new or useful formula and that 
abbott had committed fraud on the us patent office 
but her refusal to dismiss abbotts claims makes a trial more 
likely in a suit that poses a serious threat to genentech patel set 
a tentative trial date of january 1991 
genentechs suit filed last year seeks to stop abbott from 
claiming that genentech had violated its patents for an artificial 
protein abbott responded by countersuing genentech for patent 
infringement 
abbott first patented the substance in 1978 using a derivative 
of human kidney cells to produce the protein its patents in 1983 
and 1985 involved genetic engineering techniques 
genentech using a different process produced a similar 
substance called tpa which it sells commercially as the heart 
disease prevention drug activase abbott has not marketed its 
product commercially 
in pretrial proceedings genentech has contended that abbotts 
patent is invalid arguing it was not reliable or specific enough to 
enable others to duplicate the product by using the formula as 
patent law requires any product that could be produced from 
abbotts patent would not resemble tpa closely enough to justify a 
suit for infringement genentech argued 
but patel ruled that abbotts scientific evidence contradicted 
genentechs claims sufficiently to raise factual disputes that could 
be resovled only in a trial 
the judge did not allow genentech to back its claims with its own 
scientific testimony because of her december ruling that genentech 
had tampered with one of abbotts witnesses 
patel found that a genentech scientist had approached an abbott 
scientist improperly and tried to persuade him to change his 
testimony and that the action had been agreed to or winked at 
by genentech lawyers she prohibited genentech from using statements 
by three scientists in support of its challenge to abbotts patents 
and also disqualified three genentech lawyers from the case 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

