<TEXT>
although treasury secretary nicholas bradys 
debtreduction plan has been well received internationally the 
white house reserved judgement on it monday 
no final decision has been made in terms of an approach to 
third world debt deputy press secretary roman popadiuk told a 
white house briefing 
bradys plan which he unveilled in a speech friday has as its 
central element the partial forgiveness by commercial banks of the 
410 billion in debt run up by developing nations most of them in 
latin america 
the plan represents a major shift in administration thinking 
it would supplant a strategy developed by former treasury 
secretary james a baker iii now the secretary of state that 
ruled out debt forgiveness and called instead for new loans by banks 
to countries that institute economic reforms 
this previous strategy known as the baker plan produced 
little in the way of new bank loans however in his speech friday 
brady all but conceded that the past strategy had failed to solve 
the debt crisis 
the brady plan has received generally favorable reviews both at 
home and abroad but disagreement remained within the govrnment over 
details administration sources said 
deputy treasury secretary david mulford said monday that bradys 
points were put forward as ideas and suggestions for debate 
among countries and institutions and not as a definite plan 
in a briefing on the proposals for foreign reporters mulford 
insisted bradys plan enjoyed broad support within the bush 
administration 
asked about reports of disagreements with the federal reserve 
system which is independent of the administration mulford said 
im not aware of any deep division between us on these 
suggestions 
mulford said it would be our hope that policy changes will be 
in place within a matter of some months to cut the debts and 
interest payments of third world countries 
still on friday and again on monday the white house appeared to 
be going out of its way to put some distance between itself and the 
new proposal 
secretary brady had a number of ideas he presented those 
ideas the president was aware of those ideas popadiuk said 
and he said while brady as treasury secretary speaks for the 
administration on such matters no final decision has been 
reached by bush on whether to embrace the approach 
popadiuk said the outline that brady offered remains under 
consideration 
while remaining noncommittal popadiuk characterized the brady 
proposal as one that builds on the baker plan rather than 
repudidating it 
a white house official who spoke on the condition of anonymity 
said that baker had signed off on his successors propsal 
brady isnt out there alone on it the official said 
the official said that the main reason for the delay in giving 
the proposal official white house blessings was that the plan needed 
to be mulled over further by aides and by interagency groups 
bradys plan calls for banks to forgive part of the outstanding 
debt by using money from the world bank and the international 
monetary fund as collateral 
the plan also envisions that some of the debt will be swapped by 
banks for bonds of lower face value 
</TEXT>
